{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524461"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14000"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14000"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.04,0.06,0.03,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98811"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6649"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81202"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2234"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"7866"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33923"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98811"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of recurrent fevers. He underwent a laparoscopic excision of an epiphrenic diverticulum three weeks ago and initially made an uneventful recovery. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks four standard drinks per week socially. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals dullness to percussion at the right base. A CT scan of the chest is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Empyema","Pneumonia","Pleural effusion","Haemothorax","Lung abscess"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eempyema\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s history of recent thoracic surgery, presentation with fever, and CT findings are highly suggestive of this condition (Image). Empyema is characterised by the accumulation of pus and fibrous material in the pleural space, often as a complication of a reactive inflammatory response such as pneumonia or thoracic surgery. Management would typically involve antibiotics and drainage of the empyema, either by tube thoracostomy or surgical intervention, depending on the stage and extent of the empyema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe CT image shows a loculated fluid collection with enhancing walls in the right hemithorax, which is characteristic of empyema. The loculations and thickened pleura distinguish it from a simple \u003Cstrong\u003Epleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E, which would appear as a homogeneous fluid collection without internal septations or pleural enhancement and thin pleural surfaces. Empyemas often show an obtuse angle with the chest wall and may be biconvex in shape rather than concave for pleural effusions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with consolidation on CT, appearing as areas of increased density in the lung parenchyma, often with air bronchograms. Aspiration pneumonia should be considered post-surgery. However, while pneumonia can lead to empyema, the CT findings here are more consistent with an established empyema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elung abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a cavitary lesion within the lung parenchyma rather than the anatomical space, often with an air-fluid level. A lung abscess is usually the result of a pulmonary infection, with the abscess being within the lung tissue. The patient\u0027s history does not suggest a primary lung infection and the CT image does not show this characteristic appearance. The patient\u0027s surgical procedure was within the pleural space and did not broach the lung tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemothorax\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the time elapsed since surgery and the CT appearance - it would typically present more acutely post-surgery. A haemothorax would commonly appear as a homogeneous fluid collection with higher density than a simple effusion, but without the loculations and pleural enhancement seen in empyema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Empyema should be suspected in patients with recent thoracic surgery who present with fever and respiratory symptoms."],"references":["Jones J. Empyeyma. Radiopaedia. 2024. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/empyema-1","Gupta A. Postoperative complications following thoracic surgery. In: Clinical Thoracic Anesthesia. 2020. Available at: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/342618758_Postoperative_Complications_Following_Thoracic_Surgery","Sharma R. Empyema vs pleural effusion. Radiopaedia. 2024. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/empyema-vs-pleural-effusion-2?lang=us"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81202"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14000"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20908"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21098"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20908"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hF4zzE2woTX5ryTVtFzX14xpdWrkBC.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hF4zzE2woTX5ryTVtFzX14xpdWrkBC.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":793,"height":631}},{"type":"media","id":"21098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21098"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zyeMAxeHVkQiIil8jdlev0hVSMfp1L.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zyeMAxeHVkQiIil8jdlev0hVSMfp1L.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":793,"height":631}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81202"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-17T17:14:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-17T17:14:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6649"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98811"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83